ğŸš— Multi-Mode Embedded Autonomous & Remote-Controlled Robot Car
ğŸ“Œ Project Overview

This project is a multi-mode embedded robot car designed and implemented as part of an Embedded Systems course.
The system integrates autonomous navigation, infrared remote control, and Bluetooth mobile control into a single, unified control architecture.

The robot demonstrates sensor integration, real-time motor control, UART communication, and mode arbitration, making it a complete embedded control system rather than a single-sensor demo.

âš™ï¸ Features

ğŸ¤– Autonomous Obstacle Avoidance

Ultrasonic distance sensing

Servo-based left/right scanning

Dynamic path selection based on free space

ğŸ“º IR Remote Control Mode (KY-022)

Real-time manual control using an IR remote

Immediate override of autonomous behavior

ğŸ“± Bluetooth Control Mode (HC-06 / ZS-040)

Android phone control via Bluetooth

UART communication using SoftwareSerial

Simple character-based command protocol

ğŸ” Multi-Mode Architecture

Three operating modes: Autonomous, IR, Bluetooth

Only one active mode at a time

Manual modes have higher priority than autonomous mode

ğŸ§  System Architecture

The system is implemented as a state-based controller, where each input source (ultrasonic sensor, IR receiver, Bluetooth module) is handled independently.
A mode controller ensures safe arbitration so that motor outputs are driven by only one control source at any time.

Control Priority:

Bluetooth (highest)

IR Remote

Autonomous Navigation (default)

